Section 1: Q&A; Pairs

Example 1.1

User

What is mean squared error?
AI Response

MSE is (1/n) * sum of (predicted - actual)^2. It penalizes large errors heavily and is a standard loss function
for regression tasks, sensitive to outliers.

Example 1.2

User

What is transfer learning?
AI Response

Transfer learning reuses a model trained on one task as a starting point for another related task, reducing
training time and data requirements significantly.

Example 1.3

User

What is RLHF?
AI Response

Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback trains a reward model on human preference data, then uses
RL (PPO) to fine-tune an LLM to produce outputs humans prefer.

Example 1.4

User

What is a neural network?
AI Response

A neural network is a series of algorithms modeled after the human brain, consisting of input, hidden, and
output layers, with weights adjusted during training to minimize prediction error.

Example 1.5

User

What is cross-validation?
AI Response

Cross-validation splits data into k folds, training on k-1 and validating on one, rotating until all folds serve as
validation. Results are averaged for robust performance estimation.

Example 1.6

User

What is a convolutional neural network?
AI Response

A CNN uses convolutional layers to automatically learn spatial features from images. Pooling layers reduce
dimensionality. CNNs are the standard for image classification and detection tasks.

Example 1.7

User

What is zero-shot learning?
AI Response



Zero-shot learning predicts unseen classes by leveraging semantic relationships or natural language task
descriptions, allowing LLMs to generalize without task-specific training.

Example 1.8

User

What is the bias-variance tradeoff?
AI Response

High bias = underfitting (oversimplified model); high variance = overfitting (over-complex model). Good
models balance both to minimize total prediction error.

Example 1.9

User

What is overfitting?
AI Response

Overfitting occurs when a model learns training data too well—including noise—causing poor generalization
to new data. Symptoms include high train accuracy but low validation accuracy.

Example 1.10

User

What is data augmentation?
AI Response

Data augmentation artificially increases training data by applying transformations like rotation, cropping, and
flipping to existing samples, improving model generalization.



